Transfer Learning!¶

Now that you have a good training set, it's time to transfer learn! However, we will be using a feature of tensorflow known as tensorboard https://www.tensorflow.org/tensorboard to visualize the training process. One tricky thing about tensorboard is port management. In addition to port forwarding via Jupyter (likely port 8888), you need an additional port for tensorboard within Jupyter. Pick a value > 8888, say, 8890, and setup your SSH/Putty to port forward that as well. Now, note this port here and you should be all set:

def load_lung_seg_model(model_path, weights_path):
    """ Loads the lung segmentation model built by Brian Hurt, MD, MS (AiDA Lab)

    Args:
        model_path:   path to lung segmentation model architecture
        weights_path: path to lung segmentation model weights

    Returns:
        lung segmentation model (keras Model class) with weights loaded
    """
    # load liver segmentation model
    json_file = open(model_path, 'r'); loaded_model_json = json_file.read()
    json_file.close()
    
    # load model weights
    model = tf.keras.models.model_from_json(loaded_model_json)
    model.load_weights(weights_path) # Load model weights
    
    return model

# Loss = 1 - DICE Function 
def dice_coef_loss_6ch(y_true, y_pred):
    """ Loss = 1 - Dice function built by Evan Masutani, (AiDA Lab)

    Args:
        y_true:   a channels label 
        y_pred: a channels prediction

    Returns:
        lung tupel with Loss = 1 - Dice for each channel
    """
    smooth = 1.
    # Channel 0
    y_true_f_0 = tf.keras.backend.flatten(y_true[...,0])
    y_pred_f_0 = tf.keras.backend.flatten(y_pred[...,0])
    intersection_0 = tf.keras.backend.sum( y_true_f_0 * y_pred_f_0 )
    dice_0 = (2 * intersection_0 + smooth) / (tf.keras.backend.sum(y_true_f_0) + tf.keras.backend.sum(y_pred_f_0) + smooth)
    dice_0_loss = 1. - dice_0
    # Channel 1
    y_true_f_1 = tf.keras.backend.flatten(y_true[...,1])
    y_pred_f_1 = tf.keras.backend.flatten(y_pred[...,1])
    intersection_1 = tf.keras.backend.sum( y_true_f_1 * y_pred_f_1 )
    dice_1 = (2 * intersection_1 + smooth) / (tf.keras.backend.sum(y_true_f_1) + tf.keras.backend.sum(y_pred_f_1) + smooth)
    dice_1_loss = 1. - dice_1
    # Channel 2
    y_true_f_2 = tf.keras.backend.flatten(y_true[...,2])
    y_pred_f_2 = tf.keras.backend.flatten(y_pred[...,2])
    intersection_2 = tf.keras.backend.sum( y_true_f_2 * y_pred_f_2 )
    dice_2 = (2 * intersection_2 + smooth) / (tf.keras.backend.sum(y_true_f_2) + tf.keras.backend.sum(y_pred_f_2) + smooth)
    dice_2_loss = 1. - dice_2
    # Channel 3
    y_true_f_3 = tf.keras.backend.flatten(y_true[...,3])
    y_pred_f_3 = tf.keras.backend.flatten(y_pred[...,3])
    intersection_3 = tf.keras.backend.sum( y_true_f_3 * y_pred_f_3 )
    dice_3 = (2 * intersection_3 + smooth) / (tf.keras.backend.sum(y_true_f_3) + tf.keras.backend.sum(y_pred_f_3) + smooth)
    dice_3_loss = 1. - dice_3
    # Channel 4
    y_true_f_4 = tf.keras.backend.flatten(y_true[...,4])
    y_pred_f_4 = tf.keras.backend.flatten(y_pred[...,4])
    intersection_4 = tf.keras.backend.sum( y_true_f_4 * y_pred_f_4 )
    dice_4 = (2 * intersection_4 + smooth) / (tf.keras.backend.sum(y_true_f_4) + tf.keras.backend.sum(y_pred_f_4) + smooth)
    dice_4_loss = 1. - dice_4
    # Channel 5
    y_true_f_5 = tf.keras.backend.flatten(y_true[...,5])
    y_pred_f_5 = tf.keras.backend.flatten(y_pred[...,5])
    intersection_5 = tf.keras.backend.sum( y_true_f_5 * y_pred_f_5 )
    dice_5 = (2 * intersection_5 + smooth) / (tf.keras.backend.sum(y_true_f_5) + tf.keras.backend.sum(y_pred_f_5) + smooth)
    dice_5_loss = 1. - dice_5
    return(dice_0_loss + dice_1_loss + dice_2_loss + dice_3_loss + dice_4_loss + dice_5_loss)

To create a new CXR_TL_UNet¶

In [ ]:
# Open pre-processed images (train/validation/test)
inh5 = h5py.File(INH5,'r')

# Give our model a name
modelname = 'CXR_TL_UNet'

# Direct a savepath for our model
MODELPATH = Directory + modelname + '.hdf5'

# Define a batch size for the model
batch_size = 10 #this way 20 iterations per epcoh (20 images before weights are updated)

# We now need to define a data generator, which feeds chunks of data from the hdf5 file to tensorflow, 
# rather than the whole thing
def model_generator(inputpath, img_key, label_key, batch_size, partitionN):
    start_idx = 0
    end_idx = batch_size
    while True:
        if end_idx > partitionN:
            start_idx = 0
            end_idx = batch_size
        batch_img = HDF5Matrix(inputpath, img_key, start=start_idx, end=end_idx)
        batch_label = HDF5Matrix(inputpath, label_key, start=start_idx, end=end_idx)
        start_idx = start_idx + batch_size
        end_idx = end_idx + batch_size
        yield batch_img, batch_label
        
## Define the dimensions of our dataset
trainingN = inh5['training_images'].shape[0]
validationN = inh5['validation_images'].shape[0]
testingN = inh5['testing_images'].shape[0]

# Define steps per epoch and number of validation steps for training the model
steps_per_epoch = np.floor(trainingN / batch_size)
validation_steps = np.floor(validationN / batch_size)

# multi gpu https://www.tensorflow.org/guide/distributed_training
mirrored_strategy = tf.distribute.MirroredStrategy()

print ('Number of devices: {}'.format(mirrored_strategy.num_replicas_in_sync))
with mirrored_strategy.scope():
    lung_model = load_lung_seg_model(MODEL, WEIGHTS) #previously
    #lung_model = keras.models.load_model(third_TL_Model, compile = False)
    NCHANNELSout = 6 # Number of output channels
    # Start from 2nd to last layer in lung model, new output layer to handle multichannels
    # https://github.com/keras-team/keras/issues/8772
    conv_out = Conv2D(NCHANNELSout, (3,3), activation = 'sigmoid', padding = 'same', kernel_initializer = 'he_normal', name='conv_out2')(lung_model.layers[-4].output)

    CXR_TL_model = tf.keras.Model(lung_model.inputs, conv_out)
    # Set  lr to Brian's lr = 1e-4 but loss to 1 - DICE instead of MAE
    CXR_TL_model.compile(optimizer = Adam(lr = 1e-4), loss = dice_coef_loss_6ch) 
    # print the summary
    CXR_TL_model.summary()

    # Make a dir for our tensorboard
    try:
        os.mkdir(Directory + '/tensorboard')
    except:
        print('directory exists')

    logdir = os.path.join("logs", datetime.datetime.now().strftime("%Y%m%d-%H%M%S"))
    tensorboard_callback = tf.keras.callbacks.TensorBoard(logdir, histogram_freq=1)
    
    # Define our callbacks:
    # Early stopping terminates training once val_loss increases for more than patience times
    # ModelCheckpoint will save model weights only on improvement based on val_loss

    callbacks = [EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=50),
                 ModelCheckpoint(filepath=MODELPATH, monitor='val_loss', save_best_only=True),
                tensorboard_callback]
    
    #increase weight the channels that performed poorly
    class_weight =  {0: 1.,
                     1: 1., 
                     2: 1., 
                     4: 5., 
                     5: 5., 
                     6: 1.}
    
    # Train our model with our generator!
    %tensorboard --logdir logs --port=8866
    CXR_TL_model.fit(
        model_generator(INH5, 'training_images', 'training_labels', batch_size, trainingN),
        epochs=500,
        steps_per_epoch=steps_per_epoch,
        validation_data=model_generator(INH5, 'validation_images', 'validation_labels', batch_size, validationN),
        validation_steps=validation_steps,
        callbacks=callbacks, 
        class_weight=class_weight)

# DICE FUNCTIONS

print(test_predictions.shape)
print(test_labels.shape)

def dice_fxn(pred, label, cutoff):
    smooth = 0.000001
    pred = np.ravel(pred)
    label = np.ravel(label)
    pred[pred > cutoff] = 1.
    pred[pred < 1] = 0
    label[label > cutoff] = 1.
    label[label < 1] = 0
    intersection = np.sum( pred * label )
    dice = (2 * intersection + smooth) / (np.sum(pred) + np.sum(label) + smooth)
    return dice

print(len(test_predictions))
results = np.zeros((test_labels.shape[0], test_labels.shape[-1]))
# for DICE function
for i in range(len(test_labels)):
    for ch in range(test_predictions.shape[-1]):
        results[i,ch] = dice_fxn(test_predictions[i,...,ch], test_labels[i,...,ch], cutoff = 0.5)

print('overall DICE' , np.mean(results))

anatomy = ['right lung', 'left lung', 'mediastinum', 'right clavicle', 'left clavicle', 'spine']

for ch in range(results.shape[-1]):
    print(anatomy[ch] , np.mean(results[:,...,ch]))

# DICE for Brian's Model

# Let's make a swarm plot of pairwise cnn performance
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(9,9))
ax1 = plt.subplot(1,1,1)
ax1 = sns.boxplot(data=[results[:,0], results[:,1]], color=".3")
ax1 = sns.swarmplot(data=[results[:,0], results[:,1]])
plt.title('DICE Performace')
plt.xticks([0,1,2], ('right lung', 'left lung'))
ax1.set_ylabel('DICE')

# what index are the outliers? or ones that are less than DICE = 0.8
Q1 = np.zeros(results.shape[-1])
Q3 = np.zeros(results.shape[-1])
IQR = np.zeros(results.shape[-1])
anatomy = ['right lung', 'left lung', 'mediastinum', 'right clavicle', 'left clavicle', 'spine']
for ch in range(results.shape[-1]):
    Q1[ch] = np.quantile(results[:,...,ch], 0.25)
    Q3[ch] = np.quantile(results[:,...,ch], 0.75)
    IQR[ch] = Q3[ch] - Q1[ch]
    print( anatomy[ch] ,
          '\n\t outlier DICE: ',
          np.where((results[:,...,ch] < (Q1[ch] - 1.5 * IQR[ch])) | (results[:,...,ch] > (Q3[ch] + 1.5 * IQR[ch]))),
          '\n\t DICE < 0.8: ',
          np.where(results[:,...,ch] < 0.8))

# Colorful Masks overlay on xray for Paper (or Instagram)

import cv2
from matplotlib.colors import LinearSegmentedColormap, ListedColormap
import matplotlib.cm as cm
from collections.abc import Iterable

testix = 0

def _create_tricolor_cmap(highcolor,
                          middlecolor,
                          lowcolor,
                          high_alpha=0.5,
                          middle_alpha=0.5,
                          low_alpha=0.5,
                          stretch_high=0.51,
                          stretch_low=0.49):

    stretch_high, stretch_low = stretch_high, stretch_low
    cmap = LinearSegmentedColormap.from_list("", [(0, lowcolor),(stretch_low, middlecolor),
                                                  (stretch_high, middlecolor),
                                                  (1.0, highcolor)
                                                  ]
                                             )
    prob_cmap = cmap(np.arange(cmap.N))  # Get the colormap colors
    prob_cmap[..., -1] = middle_alpha * np.ones(cmap.N)
    n_negative, n_positive = int(stretch_low * cmap.N), int(stretch_high * cmap.N)
    prob_cmap[:n_negative, -1] = np.linspace(low_alpha, middle_alpha, n_negative)
    prob_cmap[-n_positive:, -1] = np.linspace(middle_alpha, high_alpha, n_positive)
    prob_cmap = ListedColormap(prob_cmap)  # Create new colormap
    return prob_cmap


def single(color, high_alpha=0.5, mid_alpha=0.05, low_alpha=0.01):
    return _create_tricolor_cmap(color, color, color, stretch_high=0.7, stretch_low=0.3, high_alpha=high_alpha,
                                 middle_alpha=mid_alpha, low_alpha=low_alpha)

def plot_img(im_arr, ax=None):
    """Display image array on axes.
    :param im_arr: 2-D numpy array
    :param ax: matplotlib axes instance

    :return: matplotlib axes instance
    """
    if ax is None:
        f, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(8,8))
    ax.imshow(im_arr, cmap="gray")
    return ax


def plot_prediction(mask, ax=None, color=None, resize=(256, 256)):
    if ax is None:
        f, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(8,8))

    cmap = single(color)
    if isinstance(resize, Iterable):
        image = cv2.resize(mask, tuple(resize))
    _ = ax.imshow(image, interpolation='nearest', vmin=0, vmax=1, cmap=cmap)
    return ax

fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(6, 6))
